<subSubSection id="F6B211C39E7F931FA3A8FF5FFA41DBEA" pageId="38" pageNumber="39" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph id="BE1742489E7F931FA3A8FF5FFA41DBEA" blockId="38.[151,1436,151,428]" pageId="38" pageNumber="39">
<emphasis id="8CDC9E5A9E7F931FA3A8FF5FFE0CDAB9" bold="true" box="[199,462,187,212]" inLineHeading="true" pageId="38" pageNumber="39" reason="1">Differential diagnosis.</emphasis>
The habitus of 
<taxonomicName id="79A839CB9E7F931FA111FF59FD3BDAB9" box="[638,761,189,212]" class="Insecta" family="Epimetopidae" genus="Epimetopus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="38" pageNumber="39" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="costatus">
<emphasis id="8CDC9E5A9E7F931FA111FF59FD3BDAB9" box="[638,761,189,212]" italics="true" pageId="38" pageNumber="39">E. costatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<figureCitation id="26935ECD9E7F931FA066FF58FC99DAB9" box="[777,859,188,212]" captionStart="FIGURES 65–68" captionStartId="36.[151,263,1726,1749]" captionTargetBox="[219,1357,207,1691]" captionTargetId="figure-134@36.[211,1376,193,1705]" captionTargetPageId="36" captionText="FIGURES 65–68. Epimetopus, dorsal and lateral habitus, and perpendicular to pronotum, holotypes and lectotype of E. costatus." pageId="38" pageNumber="39">Fig. 67</figureCitation>
) is very similar to that of several other members of the 
<emphasis id="8CDC9E5A9E7F931FA3AEFF04FEE1DA95" box="[193,291,224,248]" italics="true" pageId="38" pageNumber="39">Costatus</emphasis>
group; reliable determinations will be based on examination of the aedeagus. The aedeagus (
<figureCitation id="26935ECD9E7F931FA62EFF3BFA56DA9A" box="[1345,1428,223,247]" captionStart="FIGURES 69–72" captionStartId="37.[151,264,2007,2030]" captionTargetBox="[222,1365,677,1986]" captionTargetId="figure-145@37.[196,1390,658,2020]" captionTargetPageId="37" captionText="FIGURES 69–72. Epimetopus, aedeagi of holotypes, and lectotype of E. costatus." pageId="38" pageNumber="39">Fig. 71</figureCitation>
) has a very distinctive median lobe, which is markedly widened at the distal one-third. It is nearest in form to the aedeagus of 
<taxonomicName id="79A839CB9E7F931FA24AFECDFE7BDB52" authorityName="Perkins" authorityYear="2012" box="[293,441,296,320]" class="Insecta" family="Epimetopidae" genus="Epimetopus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="38" pageNumber="39" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="arizonicus">
<emphasis id="8CDC9E5A9E7F931FA24AFECDFE7BDB52" box="[293,441,296,320]" italics="true" pageId="38" pageNumber="39">E. arizonicus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<figureCitation id="26935ECD9E7F931FA2A5FEC3FDDCDB52" box="[458,542,295,319]" captionStart="FIGURES 69–72" captionStartId="37.[151,264,2007,2030]" captionTargetBox="[222,1365,677,1986]" captionTargetId="figure-145@37.[196,1390,658,2020]" captionTargetPageId="37" captionText="FIGURES 69–72. Epimetopus, aedeagi of holotypes, and lectotype of E. costatus." pageId="38" pageNumber="39">Fig. 70</figureCitation>
), but that species has a much narrower and longer median lobe, which extends further beyond the slightly differently shaped parameres. Externally (
<figureCitation id="26935ECD9E7F931FA0CAFEA8FBEDDB09" box="[933,1071,332,356]" captionStart="FIGURES 65–68" captionStartId="36.[151,263,1726,1749]" captionTargetBox="[219,1357,207,1691]" captionTargetId="figure-134@36.[211,1376,193,1705]" captionTargetPageId="36" captionText="FIGURES 65–68. Epimetopus, dorsal and lateral habitus, and perpendicular to pronotum, holotypes and lectotype of E. costatus." pageId="38" pageNumber="39">Figs. 66, 67</figureCitation>
), the two species differ in color, 
<taxonomicName id="79A839CB9E7F931FA3F8FE95FED0DBE5" box="[151,274,369,392]" class="Insecta" family="Epimetopidae" genus="Epimetopus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="38" pageNumber="39" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="costatus">
<emphasis id="8CDC9E5A9E7F931FA3F8FE95FED0DBE5" box="[151,274,369,392]" italics="true" pageId="38" pageNumber="39">E. costatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is reddish and 
<taxonomicName id="79A839CB9E7F931FA2D4FE95FD8DDBEA" authorityName="Perkins" authorityYear="2012" box="[443,591,368,392]" class="Insecta" family="Epimetopidae" genus="Epimetopus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="38" pageNumber="39" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="arizonicus">
<emphasis id="8CDC9E5A9E7F931FA2D4FE95FD8DDBEA" box="[443,591,368,392]" italics="true" pageId="38" pageNumber="39">E. arizonicus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is brown, and 
<taxonomicName id="79A839CB9E7F931FA19BFE95FCB2DBE5" box="[756,880,369,392]" class="Insecta" family="Epimetopidae" genus="Epimetopus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="38" pageNumber="39" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="costatus">
<emphasis id="8CDC9E5A9E7F931FA19BFE95FCB2DBE5" box="[756,880,369,392]" italics="true" pageId="38" pageNumber="39">E. costatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has the non-carinate elytral intervals smoother.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
